snippet.textDisplay:
A 33-year-old German man may be the first European to have contracted the infection of the new coronavirus and to have transmitted it. This was reported by a letter from German doctors published in the New England Journal of Medicine on March 5. The man experienced respiratory symptoms and high fever on January 24th. The symptoms improved and he returned to work on January 27th. On 20 and 21 January she attended a meeting in which a colleague from Shanghai was present, who remained in Germany from 19 to 22 January without experiencing any disturbance.

According to a genetic map published on the Netxstrain website, which reconstructs a sort of genealogical tree of the virus, the German outbreak could have silently fed the chain of infections to the point of being connected to many cases in Europe and in Italy. By analyzing the pathway and genetic mutations of the coronavirus, the researchers found that it entered Europe several times. "Since February 1, around a quarter of new infections in Mexico, Finland, Scotland and Italy, like the first cases in Brazil, appear genetically similar to the Munich outbreak," notes Bedford.

snippet.textDisplay: Stop fear mongering
snippet.textOriginal: Stop fear mongering

snippet.textDisplay: During this period of panic/hysteria, I for one cannot help THINK that a "temporary" cashless society may well be on the horizon. This "killer" bug is spread by coughing. Everyone in every society handles money. Could it not be an easy sell RIGHT HERE & NOW to convince the masses that a major way to stop the spread of this virus is to "temporarily" ban the use of cash? RIGHT HERE & NOW, masses of people will be up for that. All transactions until your told otherwise are to be electronic. I warn you now, IF this is what you're to be told in coming hours, days, weeks etc -   BE AFRAID, BE VERY AFRAID. A cashless society could be our new reality, much quicker than what some would like to think, worst still believe - please sleep on it.
